PMID:14660795
Mono- and multisite phosphorylation enhances Bcl2's antiapop... 		REMOVE
Summary: MISANNOTATION: Bcl2 (Apoptosis regulator) does NOT catalyze phosphorylation. PMID:14660795 titled "Mono- and multisite phosphorylation enhances Bcl2's antiapoptotic function" describes Bcl2 being PHOSPHORYLATED (as substrate) - "Single-site phosphorylation at serine 70 (S70) is required for Bcl2's antiapoptotic function". UniProt confirms Bcl2 is phosphorylated BY PKC, ERKs, stress-activated kinases, and MAPK8/JNK1 at Thr-69, Ser-70, and Ser-84. Bcl2 is a membrane protein with BH domains that regulates apoptosis - it has NO kinase activity. This annotation incorrectly implies Bcl2 catalyzes phosphorylation when it is actually the TARGET of phosphorylation.
Supporting Evidence:
PMID:14660795
Mono- and multisite phosphorylation enhances Bcl2's antiapoptotic function and inhibition of cell cycle entry functions.

      id: GO:0018105
      label: peptidyl-serine phosphorylation
    evidence_type: IDA
    original_reference_id: PMID:14660795
    review:
      summary: >-
        MISANNOTATION: Bcl2 (Apoptosis regulator) does NOT catalyze phosphorylation.
        PMID:14660795
        titled "Mono- and multisite phosphorylation enhances Bcl2's antiapoptotic
        function"
        describes Bcl2 being PHOSPHORYLATED (as substrate) - "Single-site phosphorylation
        at
        serine 70 (S70) is required for Bcl2's antiapoptotic function". UniProt confirms
        Bcl2
        is phosphorylated BY PKC, ERKs, stress-activated kinases, and MAPK8/JNK1 at
        Thr-69,
        Ser-70, and Ser-84. Bcl2 is a membrane protein with BH domains that regulates
        apoptosis - it has NO kinase activity. This annotation incorrectly implies
        Bcl2
        catalyzes phosphorylation when it is actually the TARGET of phosphorylation.
      action: REMOVE
      supported_by:
        - reference_id: PMID:14660795
          supporting_text: Mono- and multisite phosphorylation enhances Bcl2's 
            antiapoptotic function and inhibition of cell cycle entry functions.
